           MakeBoxes[Tabular`Typesetting`TableView`Private`val]][
          "Identify the underlying pattern in this series and explain it: 1, \
2, 6, 24, 120", {50, 5}]], 
         RawBoxes[
          
          Function[{
           Tabular`Typesetting`TableView`Private`val, 
            Tabular`Typesetting`TableView`Private`pos}, 
           MakeBoxes[Tabular`Typesetting`TableView`Private`val]][
          "The series given is: 1, 2, 6, 24, 120.\n\nTo identify the pattern, \
let's examine the relationship between consecutive numbers:\n\n- \\(1\\) to \
\\(2\\): Multiply by \\(2\\) (or \\(1 \\times 2\\)).\n- \\(2\\) to \\(6\\): \
Multiply by \\(3\\) (or \\(2 \\times 3\\)).\n- \\(6\\) to \\(24\\): Multiply \
by \\(4\\) (or \\(6 \\times 4\\)).\n- \\(24\\) to \\(120\\): Multiply by \\(5\
\\) (or \\(24 \\times 5\\)).\n\nThe pattern is that each term is obtained by \
multiplying the previous term by an increasing integer. Specifically, each \
term \\(a_n\\) is the product of all integers from \\(1\\) to \\(n\\), which \
is the definition of a factorial.\n\nThus, the series represents the \
factorial of integers starting from \\(1!\\):\n\n- \\(1! = 1\\)\n- \\(2! = 2 \
\\times 1 = 2\\)\n- \\(3! = 3 \\times 2 \\times 1 = 6\\)\n- \\(4! = 4 \\times \
3 \\times 2 \\times 1 = 24\\)\n- \\(5! = 5 \\times 4 \\times 3 \\times 2 \
\\times 1 = 120\\)\n\nTherefore, the underlying pattern is the factorial of \
consecutive natural numbers.", {50, 6}]], 
         RawBoxes[
          
          Function[{
           Tabular`Typesetting`TableView`Private`val, 
            Tabular`Typesetting`TableView`Private`pos}, 
