              "\"You can use a regular expression in Python to match a word \
that contains the letter 'z', ensuring that 'z' is not at the start or end of \
the word. Here's a function that does this:\\n\\n```python\\nimport \
re\\n\\ndef match_word_with_z(word):\\n    # Regular expression to match a \
word containing 'z' not at the start or end\\n    pattern = \
r'^[^z].*z.*[^z]$'\\n    return bool(re.match(pattern, word))\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nprint(match_word_with_z(\\\"crazy\\\"))  # \
True\\nprint(match_word_with_z(\\\"zebra\\\"))  # \
False\\nprint(match_word_with_z(\\\"buzz\\\"))   # \
True\\nprint(match_word_with_z(\\\"pizza\\\"))  # \
True\\nprint(match_word_with_z(\\\"z\\\"))      # False\\n```\\n\\n### Final \
Answer:\\nThe function `match_word_with_z(word)` returns `True` if the word \
contains 'z' not at the start or end; otherwise, it returns `False`.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
