              "\"You can create a Python function that takes two ranges as \
input and returns points from each range with the condition that no point \
lies in both ranges. Here's one way to implement this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
choose_points_from_ranges(range1, range2):\\n    # Convert ranges to sets for \
easy comparison\\n    set1 = set(range1)\\n    set2 = set(range2)\\n    \\n   \
 # Find points that are not in both ranges\\n    unique_points1 = set1 - set2\
\\n    unique_points2 = set2 - set1\\n    \\n    # Choose one point from each \
unique set if available\\n    point1 = unique_points1.pop() if unique_points1 \
else None\\n    point2 = unique_points2.pop() if unique_points2 else None\\n  \
  \\n    return point1, point2\\n\\n# Example usage:\\nrange1 = range(1, 10)  \
# Points from 1 to 9\\nrange2 = range(5, 15)  # Points from 5 to 14\\npoints \
= choose_points_from_ranges(range1, range2)\\nprint(points)\\n```\\n\\n### \
Final Answer\\nThe function `choose_points_from_ranges` returns two points \
from the specified ranges such that no point lies in both ranges.\""}}, 
