             "To find the largest subset where each pair of numbers is \
divisible, you can follow these steps to implement a function in Python. \
Here's a concise version of the algorithm:\n\n1. Sort the input array.\n2. \
Use dynamic programming to find the largest divisible subset.\n\nHere\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s how you can implement this:\n\n```python\ndef \
largest_divisible_subset(nums):\n    if not nums:\n        return []\n\n    # \
Sort the array\n    nums.sort()\n    n = len(nums)\n    \n    # Initialize \
the dp array and the previous index array\n    dp = [1] * n\n    prev = [-1] \
* n\n    \n    max_size = 1\n    max_index = 0\n    \n    # Build the dp \
array\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(i):\n            if \
nums[i] % nums[j] == 0:\n                if dp[j] + 1 > dp[i]:\n              \
      dp[i] = dp[j] + 1\n                    prev[i] = j\n        if dp[i] > \
max_size:\n            max_size = dp[i]\n            max_index = i\n\n    # \
Reconstruct the largest divisible subset\n    result = []\n    while \
max_index != -1:\n        result.append(nums[max_index])\n        max_index = \
prev[max_index]\n    \n    return result[::-1]  # Reverse to get the correct \
order\n\n# Example usage:\nnums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12]\n\
print(largest_divisible_subset(nums))  # Output: [1, 2, 4, 12] or [1, 3, 6]\n\
```\n\n### Explanation:\n- The function `largest_divisible_subset` takes a \
list of integers `nums`.\n- It sorts the list and initializes two arrays: \
`dp` to keep track of the size of the largest subset ending at each index and \
`prev` to reconstruct the subset.\n- It iterates through each pair of \
elements to check if one is divisible by the other and updates the `dp` and \
`prev` arrays accordingly.\n- Finally, it reconstructs the largest subset by \
backtracking through the `prev` array and returns it in the correct order."}},
