              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a function to flatten the given tuple matrix into the \
tuple list with each tuple representing each column.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To flatten a given tuple matrix into a tuple list where each \
tuple represents a column, you can use the following function in \
Python:\\n\\n```python\\ndef flatten_tuple_matrix(matrix):\\n    # Check if \
the matrix is empty\\n    if not matrix or not matrix[0]:\\n        return \
tuple()\\n\\n    # Transpose the matrix to get columns\\n    columns = \
tuple(zip(*matrix))\\n    \\n    return columns\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nmatrix = ((1, 2, 3), (4, 5, 6), (7, 8, 9))\\nflattened = \
flatten_tuple_matrix(matrix)\\nprint(flattened)  # Output: ((1, 4, 7), (2, 5, \
8), (3, 6, 9))\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. The function takes a tuple \
matrix as input.\\n2. It checks if the matrix is empty to avoid errors.\\n3. \
It uses the `zip` function with unpacking (`*`) to transpose the rows into \
columns.\\n4. The result is returned as a tuple of tuples, where each inner \
tuple represents a column.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
          Grid[{{
             Style["Prompt:", Bold], 
             "Write a function to flatten the given tuple matrix into the \
tuple list with each tuple representing each column."}, {
             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "To flatten a given tuple matrix into a tuple list where each \
tuple represents a column, you can use the following function in Python:\n\n\
```python\ndef flatten_tuple_matrix(matrix):\n    # Check if the matrix is \
empty\n    if not matrix or not matrix[0]:\n        return tuple()\n\n    # \
Transpose the matrix to get columns\n    columns = tuple(zip(*matrix))\n    \n\
    return columns\n\n# Example usage:\nmatrix = ((1, 2, 3), (4, 5, 6), (7, \
8, 9))\nflattened = flatten_tuple_matrix(matrix)\nprint(flattened)  # Output: \
((1, 4, 7), (2, 5, 8), (3, 6, 9))\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. The function \
takes a tuple matrix as input.\n2. It checks if the matrix is empty to avoid \
errors.\n3. It uses the `zip` function with unpacking (`*`) to transpose the \
rows into columns.\n4. The result is returned as a tuple of tuples, where \
each inner tuple represents a column."}}, Alignment -> {Left, Top}], {
